    "body": "### Problem\n\nCurrently, when saving the shada file (`wshada`) and then reading it in another neovim instance (`rshada`), the jumplist is merged.\n\nAfter reading the documentation of `shada-'`, I tried `'0` in my shada option, however, this seems to be ignored. \nFrom the docs:\n> ```\n> \t\t\t\t\t\t*shada-'*\n> \t'\tMaximum number of previously edited files for which the marks\n> \t\tare remembered.  This parameter must always be included when\n> \t\t'shada' is non-empty.\n> \t\tIncluding this item also means that the |jumplist| and the\n> \t\t|changelist| are stored in the shada file.\n> ```\n\nHowever, I saw in #5078 and #31890 that this seems to be expected behavior(?)\n\nSo here my question: is this a bug or is the documentation incorrect?\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Use nvim (\"instance 1\") with \n```lua\nvim.opt.shada = \"!,'0,<50,s10,h\" -- default but with '0 instead of '100\n```\n2. navigate around\n3. `:wshada`\n4. Open another nvim instance (\"instance 2\") with the settings from above\n5. `:rshada` in instance 2 -> you have the jumplist from instance 1\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nEither behave like stated in the docs (ie, respect the value of `shada-'`), or update the docs.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.11.0\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\ndon't know.\n\n### Operating system/version\n\n6.13.8-arch1-1 \n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nghostty 1.1.3-arch1\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nAUR",
